('English Language', 'NECO', 'An injunction is a pronouncement, decree, judgment or order by a court of law to refrain someone or a group from doing a particular act.', 'A pronouncement', 'A decree', 'A judgment', 'An order', NULL, 'B', 'An injunction is a pronouncement, decree, judgment or order by a court of law to refrain someone or a group from doing a particular act.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'Alleviation means the act of reducing, relieving or mitigating a challenge or anything unpleasant.', 'reducing', 'relieving', 'mitigating', 'eliminating', NULL, 'A', 'Alleviation means the act of reducing, relieving or mitigating a challenge or anything unpleasant, in the given case, poverty.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'I won''t go to the cinema with you; I have _________ the movie.', 'seen', 'been seeing', 'have seen', 'had seen', NULL, 'A', 'The sentence should read "I won''t go to the cinema with you; I have seen the movie." The appropriate verb for the space provides is present perfect verb "have seen".', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'He provided a _________ report on the recently concluded meeting.', 'on', 'about', 'for', 'of', NULL, 'A', 'In the given sentence, the appropriate preposition to collocate with the noun "report" is "on", as in "He provided a detailed report on the recently concluded meeting."', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The phrase "it''s" could be "it has" or "it is". What follows depends on the context with which it is used.', 'it has', 'it is', 'it was', 'it were', NULL, 'A', 'The phrase "it''s" could be "it has" or "it is". What follows depends on the context with which it is used. Since, the verb "been" follows "it''s", the answer is "has".', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The sentence should read "If I had known, I would not have come."', 'would', 'could', 'should', 'might', NULL, 'A', 'The sentence should read "If I had known, I would not have come." It is a subjunctive statement used to express that it is a statement that did not happen in the past when it was expected or had the chance to.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'Since the time of the day is not specified, neither "morning" nor "evening" should be preceded by article "the".', 'morning till evening', 'morning to evening', 'from morning till evening', 'from morning to evening', NULL, 'D', 'Since the time of the day is not specified, neither "morning" nor "evening" should be preceded by article "the". Note that a sentence like "I saw him in the morning" refers to a specific time of the morning, say 11am.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The sentence should read "He did it, but not quite the way I had expected".', 'quite', 'actually', 'exactly', 'so', NULL, 'A', 'The sentence should read "He did it, but not quite the way I had expected". The "quite" in the sentence means "relatively", "actually", "exactly". Note that "so" is not the right option because "the way" has been given in the sentence.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'I have _________ the cinema with you.', 'been', 'seen', 'have seen', 'had seen', NULL, 'A', 'The sentence should read "I won''t go to the cinema with you; I have seen the movie." The appropriate verb for the space is present perfect "have seen".', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The plural of "mother-in-law" is "mothers-in-law". Only mother takes the plural suffix "-s".', 'mother-in-laws', 'mothers-in-laws', 'mothers-in-law', 'mother-in-law', NULL, 'C', 'The plural of "mother-in-law" is "mothers-in-law". Only mother takes the plural suffix "-s".', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The adjective "prone" always collocates with "to". "Be prone to something" means tending to suffer from an illness or show a particular negative characteristic.', 'to', 'for', 'of', 'with', NULL, 'A', 'The adjective "prone" always collocates with "to". "Be prone to something" means tending to suffer from an illness or show a particular negative characteristic.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'Nigerian school teachers regularly meted out physical punishment to their pupils. The appropriate phrase is:', 'meted out', 'meted off', 'meted on', 'meted up', NULL, 'A', 'Met collocates with both the adverb "out" and the preposition "to" anything the phrasal verb is used.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The conjunction _________ means despite, in spite of or still.', 'yet', 'still', 'but', 'however', NULL, 'A', 'The conjunction "yet" means despite, in spite of or still. It is a contrastive conjunction appropriate for the sentence. Note that "still yet" is repetitive and so, incorrect.', NULL), 
('English Language', 'NECO', 'The sentence should read "You cannot come between my sister and me."', 'me', 'I', 'myself', 'mine', NULL, 'A', 'The sentence should read "You cannot come between my sister and me". The space provided is an object space and it needs an object pronoun — me. The sentence can be rewritten as you cannot come between us (= my sister and me).', NULL);
